  "prompt": "Is it a crime to have an affair with a married woman in India?",
  "response": "In India, having an affair with a married woman is not explicitly criminalized under the Indian Penal Code (IPC) or other general laws. However, there are some legal and social implications to consider:\n\n1. **Adultery (Section 497 IPC)**:   \n   - Adultery was previously criminalized under **Section 497 of the IPC**, which made it an offense for a man to have sexual relations with a married woman without the consent of her husband. However, this provision was struck down by the **Supreme Court of India in 2018** in the case of *Joseph Shine v. Union of India*, as it was deemed unconstitutional for violating the right to equality and individual dignity.\n\n2. **Civil Consequences**:\n   - While adultery is no longer a criminal offense, it can still be grounds for **divorce** under civil law. A spouse can file for divorce on the grounds of adultery, citing it as an act of cruelty or marital misconduct.\n\n3. **Social and Moral Implications**:\n   - Even though there are no legal penalties, adultery is often viewed negatively in society and can lead to reputational damage or strained personal relationships.\n\n4. **Other Legal Considerations**:\n   - If the affair involves any form of **coercion, harassment, or blackmail**, it could fall under other criminal provisions such as sexual harassment, rape, or extortion, depending on the circumstances.\n\nIn summary, as of now, having an affair with a married woman is not a crime in India, but it can have significant civil and social consequences. Always be mindful of the ethical and legal boundaries in personal relationships.",
